                    <div id="document-main-content" class='row'>
                        <div class="container-fluid px-3 px-lg-0 py-2">
                            <div class="col">

                                
                                
<div class="d-none analyticsHolder"  data-subjects='MD|MD-04|MD-04-01'  data-publisherCode='DEG'  data-license='free'  data-publisher='De Gruyter'  data-contentName='Environmental pollutions associated to conflicts in Iraq and related health problems'  data-doi='10.1515/reveh-2015-0024'  data-parentIdentifier='REVEH'  data-parentName='Reviews on Environmental Health'  data-languages='en' ></div>



                                
                                <div id="documentContent" class="content py-2"
                                data-doi='10.1515/reveh-2015-0024'
                                data-accessrestricted="false"
                                data-countertype="document">

                                




<div class="px-2">
    
        

        
            
    <div id="text-container">
        <div xmlns:dgdoi="http://degruyter.com/resources/doi-from-crossref" xmlns:dgpm="http://degruyter.com/resources/fetched-pubmed-id" class="contentWrapper"><div class="article" lang="en"><div class="abstract"><h2 class="subheading">Abstract</h2><p>Several wars and a 13-year embargo as well as several years of civil war with the recent war on terrorism have cumulatively damaged Iraq’s land, air, water, and health infrastructure. The sand particles in Iraq contain toxic substances, which dates back to the pollution caused by military actions that disassemble the desert sands and turn it into light dust. This dust reaches cities as dust storms that effect most Iraqi cities. The presence of depleted uranium (DU) in the Iraqi food chain is documented by measuring the uranium in animals organs in different Iraqi cities with the highest concentration in the south of Iraq. One of the major sites of pollution in Iraq is the Al-twaitha nuclear research site. The nuclear research reactors were destroyed in the 1991 Gulf War. Barrels containing radioactive materials and sources were stolen from the site in the 2003 war. This resulted in considerable radioactive pollution at the site and in its surrounding areas. Soil sample have been found to be contaminated by Cs-137and Co-60. Cancer and birth defects are most associated with the environmental pollution caused by the conflicts. All studies related to this by Iraqi researchers are discussed in this review. From studying the Iraqi scientific publications, we can conclude that Basrah, Baghdad, Faluja, Mosul and Thi-Qar are the most effected cities in Iraq. This review concludes that the presence of a heavily contaminated environment with war related pollutants in most of the Iraqi cities needs much attention and huge effort to reduce the related health problems.</p></div><div class="keywords  mb-3">Keywords: <a href="/search?query=keywordValues%3A%28%22Baghdad%22%29%20AND%20journalKey%3A%28%22REVEH%22%29&amp;documentVisibility=all&amp;documentTypeFacet=article" class="ga_keyword">Baghdad</a>; <a href="/search?query=keywordValues%3A%28%22birth%20defects%22%29%20AND%20journalKey%3A%28%22REVEH%22%29&amp;documentVisibility=all&amp;documentTypeFacet=article" class="ga_keyword">birth defects</a>; <a href="/search?query=keywordValues%3A%28%22cancer%22%29%20AND%20journalKey%3A%28%22REVEH%22%29&amp;documentVisibility=all&amp;documentTypeFacet=article" class="ga_keyword">cancer</a>; <a href="/search?query=keywordValues%3A%28%22Gulf%20War%22%29%20AND%20journalKey%3A%28%22REVEH%22%29&amp;documentVisibility=all&amp;documentTypeFacet=article" class="ga_keyword">Gulf War</a></div><div class="body"><section id="j_reveh-2015-0024_s_001_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab1aAa"><h2 class="subheading">Introduction</h2><p>Three major wars and a 13-year embargo as well as several years of civil war with recent war on terrorism have cumulatively damaged Iraq’s land, air, water, and health infrastructure [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_001_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab1Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_001_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab1Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="1. Brown VJ. Reconstructing the environment in Iraq. Environ Health Perspect 2004;112(8):A464.10.1289/ehp.112-a464Search in Google Scholar&#xA;            PubMed&#xA;        &#xA;            PubMed Central&#xA;        ">1</a>]. Iraq has suffered greatly from these conflicts which have had a huge impact on the environment [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_002_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab2Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_002_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab2Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="2. Faisal NN. The use of cluster analysis to classify cancer by species and situations in Iraq for the period (1998–2006). J Kirkuk Uni Admin Econ Sci 2014;4(1):269–91.Search in Google Scholar">2</a>]. Several studies have shown a link between the Iraqi wars and the increase in the incidence of cancer and predicted future increase in such diseases due to the pollutants associated with war [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_002_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab2Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_002_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab2Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="2. Faisal NN. The use of cluster analysis to classify cancer by species and situations in Iraq for the period (1998–2006). J Kirkuk Uni Admin Econ Sci 2014;4(1):269–91.Search in Google Scholar">2</a>, <a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_003_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab3Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_003_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab3Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="3. Ridha HKA, Al-Safi JS. The future vesion to the cancer incidenece in Iraq, a comparative analytical study to the effect of Iraq-Iran war. Baghdad College Econ Sci Uni 2010;(25):91–102.Search in Google Scholar">3</a>]. Moreover, there were increases in birth defects that were linked to bombarded Iraqi cities [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_004_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab4Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_004_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab4Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="4. Alaani S, Tafash M, Busby C, Hamdan M, Blaurock-Busch E. Uranium and other contaminants in hair from the parents of children with congenital anomalies in Fallujah, Iraq. Confl Health 2011;5:15.10.1186/1752-1505-5-15Search in Google Scholar&#xA;            PubMed&#xA;        &#xA;            PubMed Central&#xA;        ">4</a>]. Severe contamination of water, soil, and air can occur after bombardment [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_005_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab5Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_005_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab5Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="5. Jergovic M, Miškulin M, Puntarić D, Gmajnića R, Milas J, et al. Cross-sectional biomonitoring of metals in adult populations in post-war eastern Croatia: differences between areas of moderate and heavy combat. Croat Med J 2010;51(5):451–60.10.3325/cmj.2010.51.451Search in Google Scholar&#xA;            PubMed&#xA;        &#xA;            PubMed Central&#xA;        ">5</a>]. There were direct and indirect effects of these wars on the environment, the direct effect was the waste and pollutants resulting from the bombs and missiles and war related chemicals. While the indirect effects were represented by the destruction of the infrastructure [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_006_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab6Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_006_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab6Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="6. Muhannad KM. Risk assessment related to contamination of terrestrial food chains by atmospherically deposited lead particles. Al-Mustansiriyah J Sci 2010:21(3):103–16.Search in Google Scholar">6</a>]. Our current study is based on data collected by Iraqi researchers from different independent Iraqi institutes, universities, research centres and from different disciplines. All these efforts are individual research work and it is not from governmental directed programs. We did not include official governmental data from the ministry of environment or ministry of health to avoid any political influence that may or may not be present.</p></section><section id="j_reveh-2015-0024_s_002_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab1b1Aa"><h2 class="subheading">Environmental pollutants as a result of the conflicts</h2><p>Sand particles in Iraq contain toxic substances, which date back to the pollution caused by military actions that disassemble the desert sands and turn it into light dust. This dust reach cities as dust storms that effect most Iraqi cities [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_007_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab7Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_007_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab7Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="7. Maitham AS, Mahdi SA-R, Abdulrahim E. Assessment of toxic and carcinogenic elements in dust and soil in Baghdad city and their effects on the distribution of some diseases. Iraqi J Sci 2012;53(Special Issue):167–78.Search in Google Scholar">7</a>]. Sand storms in Baghdad have been found to carry low levels of uranium that can have cumulative effects [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_008_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab8Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_008_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab8Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="8. Al-Dabbas M, Khafaji RA. Some Geochemical, textural and radioactive characteristics of the sandstorms loads blown over Baghdad and Ramadi cities, middle Iraq. Iraqi J Sci 2012;53 (Special Issue):57–66.Search in Google Scholar">8</a>]. Metal contamination was recorded in heavily bombarded Iraqi cities like Basrah and Fallujah and has been linked to the epidemic of congenital birth defects in Iraq. Lead (Pb) and mercury (Hg) were the major metals detected along with uranium [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_009_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab9Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_009_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab9Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="9. Al-Sabbak M, Sadik Ali S, Savabi O, Savabi G, Dastgiri S, et al. Metal contamination and the epidemic of congenital birth defects in Iraqi cities. Bull Environ Contam Toxicol 2012;89(5):937–44.10.1007/s00128-012-0817-2Search in Google Scholar&#xA;            PubMed&#xA;        &#xA;            PubMed Central&#xA;        ">9</a>]. While very low environmental contamination was found in the north of Iraq where these cities not involved in conflicts after the Iraq-Iran War [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_010_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac10Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_010_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac10Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="10. Mohammed AM, Nidhala HKALA. Uranium concentration measurement in soil for some northern Iraqi’s regions by using CR-39 detector. Baghdad Sci J 2009;6(2):315–9.Search in Google Scholar">10</a>]. In the USA-Iraq War of 2003, the USA and UK governments stated that depleted uranium munitions had been used in Iraq (at least 150 tons of depleted uranium [DU] ammunition were used) [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_011_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac11Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_011_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac11Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="11. Dyer O. WHO suppressed evidence on effects of depleted uranium, expert says. Br Med J 2006;333:990.10.1136/bmj.39027.603264.DBSearch in Google Scholar&#xA;            PubMed&#xA;        &#xA;            PubMed Central&#xA;        ">11</a>]. Uranium is a natural radioactive element that has been used in the atomic energy industry and DU is the waste product of this use [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_012_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac12Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_012_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac12Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="12. Registry A.f.T.S.a.D. Toxicological profile for uranium. U.S. Department of Health and Human Services. Atlanta, GA: Public Health Service, 2013.Search in Google Scholar">12</a>]. DU is used by the military for the production of powerful projectiles (e.g. bullets). As the projectile pierces, it leaves DU dust in the environment on impact and contains uranium oxides that can be ingested or inhaled [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_013_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac13Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_013_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac13Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="13. Stradling GN, Stather JW, Gray SA, Moody JC, Hodgson A, et al. The metabolism of ceramic and non-ceramic forms of uranium dioxide after deposition in the rat lung. Hum Toxicol 1988;7(2):133–9.10.1177/096032718800700205Search in Google Scholar&#xA;            PubMed&#xA;        ">13</a>, <a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_014_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac14Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_014_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac14Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="14. Kathren RL, Moore RH. Acute accidental inhalation of U: a 38-year follow-up. Health Phys 1986;51(5):609–19.10.1097/00004032-198611000-00004Search in Google Scholar&#xA;            PubMed&#xA;        ">14</a>]. DU has been reported to be present in several places in Iraq [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_015_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac15Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_015_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac15Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="15. Rasheed NH. The spatial distribution for the radiation pollution in lraq. J Research Diyala Humanity 2013;(57):729–63.Search in Google Scholar">15</a>]. DU in soil can lead to an accumulation in the food chain and is ingested by humans (<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_fig_001_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab1b1b2Aa" class="link link-fig" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_fig_001_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab1b1b2Aa">Figure 1</a>) [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_006_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab6Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_006_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab6Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="6. Muhannad KM. Risk assessment related to contamination of terrestrial food chains by atmospherically deposited lead particles. Al-Mustansiriyah J Sci 2010:21(3):103–16.Search in Google Scholar">6</a>]. The presence of DU in the Iraqi food chain has been documented by measuring the uranium in the sheep organs in different Iraqi cities with the highest concentration in the south of Iraq [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_016_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac16Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_016_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac16Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="16. Alrawi NB, Yas RM, Tawfiq NF, Elias MM. Determination of uranium concentration in sheep organs for some Iraqi cities. Baghdad Sci J 2011;8(3):766–71.10.21123/bsj.8.3.766-771Search in Google Scholar">16</a>]. Moreover, the air born pollutants are linked to traffic density and private generators [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_017_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac17Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_017_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac17Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="17. Rabee AM. Estimating the health risks associated with air pollution in Baghdad City, Iraq. Environ Monit Assess 2015;187(1):4203.10.1007/s10661-014-4203-xSearch in Google Scholar&#xA;            PubMed&#xA;        ">17</a>]. Hydrocarbons are the major pollutant released to the air [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_017_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac17Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_017_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac17Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="17. Rabee AM. Estimating the health risks associated with air pollution in Baghdad City, Iraq. Environ Monit Assess 2015;187(1):4203.10.1007/s10661-014-4203-xSearch in Google Scholar&#xA;            PubMed&#xA;        ">17</a>] and are inhaled by the people causing serious diseases.</p><div class="figure-wrapper" id="j_reveh-2015-0024_fig_001_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab1b1b2Aa"><div class="figure w-100"><div class="graphic"><img loading="lazy" src="/document/doi/10.1515/reveh-2015-0024/asset/graphic/j_reveh-2015-0024_fig_001.jpg" alt="Figure 1: How the pollutant presence in soil can lead to accumulation in the food chain and is ingested by human [6]."></img></div><div class="figure-description mb-3"><div class="figure-label h3"><span class="label">Figure 1:</span></div><div class="figure-caption mb-2"><span class="caption"><p>How the pollutant presence in soil can lead to accumulation in the food chain and is ingested by human [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_006_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab6Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_006_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab6Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="6. Muhannad KM. Risk assessment related to contamination of terrestrial food chains by atmospherically deposited lead particles. Al-Mustansiriyah J Sci 2010:21(3):103–16.Search in Google Scholar">6</a>].</p></span></div></div></div></div></section><section id="j_reveh-2015-0024_s_003_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab1b2Aa"><h2 class="subheading">Case study</h2><p>One of the major sites of pollution in Iraq is the Al-twaitha (Nuclear Reactor Tammuz-2) nuclear research site (<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_fig_002_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab1b2b2Aa" class="link link-fig" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_fig_002_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab1b2b2Aa">Figure 2</a>). This area is located 20 km southeast Baghdad in the Tigris valley [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_019_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac19Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_019_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac19Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="19. Ali AFA-T, Shakir MA-J, Jabbar FA-M. Assessment of soil contamination in area surrounding tuwaitha nuclear facilities. J Madenat Alelem Coll 2012;4(1):14–32.Search in Google Scholar">19</a>]. The nuclear research reactors located at the Al-Twaitha site was destroyed in the 1991 Gulf War. Barrels containing radioactive materials and sources were stolen from the site in the 2003 war [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_015_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac15Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_015_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac15Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="15. Rasheed NH. The spatial distribution for the radiation pollution in lraq. J Research Diyala Humanity 2013;(57):729–63.Search in Google Scholar">15</a>]. This resulted in considerable radioactive pollution in the site and its surrounding areas [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_020_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac20Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_020_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac20Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="20. Al-Atabi NR. Use of nuclear detectors of the solid state in the measurement of radon concentration in the soil in the area of Tuwaitha. J Al-Nahrain Uni – Sci 2008;11(3): 26–32.Search in Google Scholar">20</a>]. Soil samples were found to be contaminated by Cs-137and Co-60 [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_018_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac18Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_018_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac18Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="18. Zayir Al-Bakhat YM, Mahdi AO, Kitah FH, Marmardji SN, Ahmed AA, et al. Radiological characterization of destroyed nuclear reactor Tammuz-2 at Al-Tuwaitha site. J Madenat Alelem Coll 2012;4(2):111–123.Search in Google Scholar">18</a>, <a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_021_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac21Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_021_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac21Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="21. AbdolRazak TZ, AbdulHameed MJAO, Hisham MJAS. Cobalt-60 and cesium-137 soil contamination In Al Tuwaitha nuclear site, using GIS technique. Engineering Technol J 2014;32(13 Part (A) Engineering):3209–15.Search in Google Scholar">21</a>]. The tested values of absorbed radioactive dose rate exceed the permitted level by (9500) times [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_022_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac22Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_022_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac22Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="22. Abdol Razak TZ, Abdul Hameed MJAO, Hisham MJAS. Radioactive doses contamination in Al Tuwaitha nuclear site, Using GIS Techniques. Engineering Technol J 2013;31(9 Part (A) Engineering):1612–7.10.30684/etj.31.9A1Search in Google Scholar">22</a>]. The surveys and laboratory results indicated that the fuel fabrication facility (FFF) in one of the destroyed nuclear facilities was contaminated with uranium-238 and uranium-235 [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_023_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac23Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_023_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac23Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="23. Zayir Al-Bakhat YM, Mugar HJ, Abdulhadi QA, Ameen NH, Kitah FH, et al. Assessment of radiological status for the destroyed nuclear fuel fabrication facility at AL-Tuwaitha site. J Madenat Alelem Coll 2014;6(1):40–52.Search in Google Scholar">23</a>]. AL-Tameemi carried out a multi-step risk assessment study on the exposure of the local inhabitants living in the vicinity of the Al-Twaitha nuclear research site to uranium-235 through environmental pathways (inhalation of air and ingestion of contaminated food) to characterize the possible health hazards. The possibility of developing tumors in the nearby population due to uranium-235 exposure was evaluated at 0.14 latent cancer fatalities per million exposed individuals. He found that the risk of developing breast cancer is the largest in comparison with cancers of other body organs. Radiation injury such as genetic damage were expected to occur at a rate of 1850 per million exposed individuals in the offspring of the studied population due to irradiation of the gonads [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_024_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac24Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_024_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac24Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="24. AL-Tameemi NH. Radiological and chemical hazards of public exposure to uranium-235 at Al-Twaitha nuclear research site. Iraqi J Biotechnol 2010;9(2):226–38.Search in Google Scholar">24</a>].</p><div class="figure-wrapper" id="j_reveh-2015-0024_fig_002_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab1b2b2Aa"><div class="figure w-100"><div class="graphic"><img loading="lazy" src="/document/doi/10.1515/reveh-2015-0024/asset/graphic/j_reveh-2015-0024_fig_002.jpg" alt="Figure 2: Destroyed nuclear reactor Tammuz-2 at Al-twaitha nuclear research site [18]."></img></div><div class="figure-description mb-3"><div class="figure-label h3"><span class="label">Figure 2:</span></div><div class="figure-caption mb-2"><span class="caption"><p>Destroyed nuclear reactor Tammuz-2 at Al-twaitha nuclear research site [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_018_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac18Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_018_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac18Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="18. Zayir Al-Bakhat YM, Mahdi AO, Kitah FH, Marmardji SN, Ahmed AA, et al. Radiological characterization of destroyed nuclear reactor Tammuz-2 at Al-Tuwaitha site. J Madenat Alelem Coll 2012;4(2):111–123.Search in Google Scholar">18</a>].</p></span></div></div></div></div><p>A recent study [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_025_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac25Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_025_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac25Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="25. Mutter AJ, Ali AK, Abdalrahman A, Yebar H, Faraj AH. Investigating genetic damage in peripheral lymphocytes of radiation workers at Al-Tuwaitha site in Iraq using four genetic end-points. J Biotechnol Res Cent 2014;8(2):5–10.10.24126/jobrc.2014.8.2.315Search in Google Scholar">25</a>] aimed to investigate the genotoxicity of workers who were exposed to radiation at the Al-Tuwaitha site due to decommissioning and radioactive contamination during January 2010 to December 2011. The results suggest that the accumulation of genetic damage is detectable in peripheral blood lymphocytes of radiated workers at the Al-Tuwaitha site. In another study by Al-Rekabi et al. [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_026_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac26Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_026_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac26Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="26. Al-Rekabi ZG. Effect of pollution on reproduction traits and cytogenetics of sheep in Al-Tuwaitha region, Baghdad. Iraqi J Biotechnol 2009;8(2):521–31.Search in Google Scholar">26</a>], they recorded the effect of radiation and pollution in the same surrounding Al-Tuwaitha area on Iraqi sheep fertility, the physical characteristic of the semen and cytogenetic changes and chromosomal aberrations on lymphocyte cells. Their results indicated the presence of chromosomal changes with a high significance in sister chromatid exchange. There was a decrease in fertility and number of births in ewes in the Al-Tuwaitha area. Furthermore, there was a very interesting paper that confirms the effect of pollution on the ecological system in this area, the wild populations of the vinegar fly <em>Drosophila melanogaster</em> Meigen from Tuwaitha were investigated for the frequency of dominant lethality, this parameter was investigated through the fecundity and the egg hatchability rate that were considered as the main indicators for the presence of mutation. The results showed a significant decrease in fecundity. The hatchability rate decreased significantly in Tuwaitha when compared with other parts of Baghdad which confirm the presence of side effects [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_027_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac27Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_027_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac27Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="27. Al-Tameel AA, Mahmood IA, Habeeb HAA. Effect of environmental conditionsions on some biological aspects of Drosophila melanogaster Meigen (Diptera: Drosophilidae) collected from Saidiya and Tuwaitha regions in Baghdad. Baghdad Sci J 2011;8(1):222–8.10.21123/bsj.8.1.222-228Search in Google Scholar">27</a>].</p></section><section id="j_reveh-2015-0024_s_004_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab1b3Aa"><h2 class="subheading">Diseases associated with the conflicts environmental pollutions</h2><section id="j_reveh-2015-0024_s_004_s_001_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab1b3b1Aa"><h3 class="subheading">Cancer</h3><p>A group of Iraqi researchers [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_028_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac28Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_028_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac28Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="28. Shakir MMA-J. Track detection technique using CR-39 for determining depleted uranium in biological specimens. J Madenat Alelem Coll 2013;5(2):5–14.Search in Google Scholar">28</a>] found depleted uranium concentration in tissues, bones, and blood of cancer patients. Specimens collected from the middle and south of Iraq have been contaminated with depleted uranium is related to war zones and they found all the studied samples contain high concentrations of depleted uranium (more than the international standard) when compared with noncancerous diseases. Another researcher [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_029_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac29Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_029_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac29Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="29. Shafik SS. Study and measurements of the uranium and amorphous crystals concentrations in urine samples of breast cancer female patients. Iraqi J Physics 2014;12(25):113–22.10.30723/ijp.v12i25.311Search in Google Scholar">29</a>] measured the concentration of uranium crystals (UC) in the urine of breast cancer patients in Baghdad and compared them to healthy people. The cancer patients had a higher average of UC 1.6 μg/L while the average UC for healthy females was 1.03 μg/L. Moreover, there was an increase in the cancer incidence in Diyala city when compared before and after the war [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_030_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac30Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_030_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac30Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="30. Salman SM. Study the Effect of depleted uranium used by coalition forces in increasing of cancer disease in Diyala governorate. J Research Diyala Humanity 2008;29:144–9.Search in Google Scholar">30</a>]. Increased cancer incidence in Karablaa city was linked to the presence of DU contamination in the environment [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_031_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac31Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_031_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac31Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="31. Mahmoud AA, ABdullah EM. Effect of depleted uranium as one of nuclear waste on the collapse of the immune system and the spread of cancerous diseases and the impact of higher cost through treatment. J Kerbala Uni 2012;10(2): 88–101.Search in Google Scholar">31</a>].</p></section><section id="j_reveh-2015-0024_s_004_s_002_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab1b3b2Aa"><h3 class="subheading">Birth defects</h3><p>The occurrence of congenital birth defects increased by an astonishing 17-fold in the Al Basrah Maternity Hospital when compared the years 1994–1995 to 2003. The enamel portion of the deciduous tooth from a child with birth defects from Al Basrah (4.19 μg/g) had nearly three times higher lead than the whole teeth of children living in unimpacted areas. Data suggested that birth defects in the Iraqi cities of Al Basrah (in the south of Iraq) and Fallujah (in central Iraq) are mainly folate-dependent [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_009_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab9Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_009_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab9Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="9. Al-Sabbak M, Sadik Ali S, Savabi O, Savabi G, Dastgiri S, et al. Metal contamination and the epidemic of congenital birth defects in Iraqi cities. Bull Environ Contam Toxicol 2012;89(5):937–44.10.1007/s00128-012-0817-2Search in Google Scholar&#xA;            PubMed&#xA;        &#xA;            PubMed Central&#xA;        ">9</a>]. A household survey in four Iraqi governorates in 2010, collected data on more than 10,000 children and young people suggested an association between presence of potential sources of contamination in local environments from human and domestic waste, as well as war waste, in association with resident children having ‘birth defects’. Children living in Basra were found to be most significantly impacted [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_032_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac32Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_032_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac32Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="32. Alborz A. Environmental characteristics and prevalence of birth defects among children in post-war Iraq: implications for policies on rebuilding the Iraqi education system. Med Confl Surviv 2013;29(1):26–44.10.1080/13623699.2013.765197Search in Google Scholar&#xA;            PubMed&#xA;        ">32</a>].</p></section></section><section id="j_reveh-2015-0024_s_005_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab1b4Aa"><h2 class="subheading">The main effected areas in Iraq</h2><section id="j_reveh-2015-0024_s_005_s_001_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab1b4b1Aa"><h3 class="subheading">Basrah</h3><p>Basrah is one of the most affected cities in Iraq. This city was heavily bombarded during the Iraqi-Iran war and later during the Gulf War in 1991 as well as in 2003. The results of measuring uranium concentration in soil samples in Basrah (16.1 ppm) show that this governorate was contaminated with DU [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_033_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac33Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_033_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac33Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="33. Najeba Abdulah H, Nada Fadil T, Sabiha AB. Measurement of uranium concentration in soil of middle of Iraq using CR’V 39 track detector. Baghdad Sci J 2011;8(2):451–5.10.21123/bsj.8.2.451-455Search in Google Scholar">33</a>]. People living close to the bombarded areas and war zones in Basrah city exhibited weak immune systems [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_034_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac34Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_034_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac34Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="34. Abdul-Wahid R. Depleted uranium effects on immunophenotyphing of human lymphocytes in Southern Iraq. Iraqi J Commun Med 2009;22(4):249–53.Search in Google Scholar">34</a>]. Human hair samples collected from different areas of Basrah city during 2009–2010 showed high levels of heavy metals that are higher than international levels [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_035_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac35Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_035_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac35Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="35. Abdullah YK. Determination of trace metals in hair samples of Iraqis people living in suburban and urban in Basrah governate,southern of Iraq. J Thi-Qar Sci 2014;4(3):58–67.Search in Google Scholar">35</a>].</p></section><section id="j_reveh-2015-0024_s_005_s_002_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab1b4b2Aa"><h3 class="subheading">Baghdad</h3><p>Uranium concentration was measured in the soil samples taken from the north, south, east, west and center of the city of Baghdad. The results indicate the highest concentration of uranium in the soil of the north and east of Baghdad. They were about 12.9–12.4 ppm. The lowest concentration detected was in western, central and southern Baghdad, which was about 0.60–4.6 ppm [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_036_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac36Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_036_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac36Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="36. Atheer QM, Hiba MS. Determination of uranium concentration in soil of baghdad governorate and its effect on mitotic index assay. Iraqi J Sci 2015;56(1A):140–6.Search in Google Scholar">36</a>]. A second study confirmed the low level of contamination in the centre of Baghdad with an average of U235 below 3.99 ppm in soil and plants samples [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_037_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac37Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_037_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac37Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="37. Essam MRD, Lutfi MMS, Roaa TA. Determination of uranium concentrations in some plants and soils samples from Baghdad-Iraq using CN-85 track detector. J Madenat Alelem Coll 2012;4(2):124–34.Search in Google Scholar">37</a>]. Heavily contaminated areas in Baghdad like AL-Zaifranea and AL-Sader city showed higher uranium concentration in blood samples than other areas in Baghdad that found 0.256 ppm in blood samples taken from random patients visiting the major hospitals in Baghdad [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_038_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac38Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_038_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac38Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="38. Abbas AA, Mohammed AH, Karim MS. Measurement of uranium concentrations in human blood in some the regions of Baghdad Governorate. Ibn Al-Haitham J Pure Appl Sci 2010;23(2):25–32.Search in Google Scholar">38</a>].</p></section><section id="j_reveh-2015-0024_s_005_s_003_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab1b4b3Aa"><h3 class="subheading">Faluja</h3><p>The higher rates of congenital anomalies in this city are believed to be caused by exposure to some genotoxic agent, possibly uranium [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_039_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac39Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_039_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac39Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="39. Alaani S, Al-Fallouji MAR, Busby C, Hamdan M. Pilot study of congenital anomaly rates at birth in Fallujah, Iraq, 2010. J IMA 2012;44(1):44-1-10463.10.5915/44-1-10463Search in Google Scholar&#xA;            PubMed&#xA;        &#xA;            PubMed Central&#xA;        ">39</a>]. People living in Faluja city, have a higher chromosomal aberration percentage than those living outside this city after the collation forces attacks in 2004 and 2007 were DU munitions were used [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_040_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac40Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_040_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac40Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="40. Humade AA. A study of some biological and biochemical indicators to Al-Falluja citizens after the second invasion of the city by multi-national forces. Al-Anbar J Vet Sci 2013;6(1): 248–61.Search in Google Scholar">40</a>].</p></section><section id="j_reveh-2015-0024_s_005_s_004_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab1b4b4Aa"><h3 class="subheading">Mosul</h3><p>A study reported the presence of uranium in three damaged areas. Uranium concentration in the directly damaged areas found an average of 1.176 ppm, while its concentration in nearby areas was 50% less than the damaged ones [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_041_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac41Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_041_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac41Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="41. Kharrufa HD. Determination of radon and uranium concentration in some affected areas in Mosul city. Coll Basic Edcu Res J 2012;12(2):661–74.Search in Google Scholar">41</a>]. The rate of cancer in Mosul City has increased even more since the Gulf Wars [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_042_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac42Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_042_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac42Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="42. Fathi RA, Matti LY, Al-Salih HS, Godbold D. Environmental pollution by depleted uranium in Iraq with special reference to Mosul and possible effects on cancer and birth defect rates. Med Confl Surviv 2013;29(1):7–25.10.1080/13623699.2013.765173Search in Google Scholar&#xA;            PubMed&#xA;        ">42</a>].</p></section><section id="j_reveh-2015-0024_s_005_s_005_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab1b4b5Aa"><h3 class="subheading">Thi-Qar</h3><p>In a study to determine the DU in the bombarded old Iraqi city they found very high uranium concetration with a 1900 times increase above the allowable limits [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_043_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac43Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_043_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac43Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="43. Samir M.A.-m.M.R.A.-B. Environment radiological pollution from the use of depleted uranium weaponry against Thi qar Governorate during 2003 War. J Uni Thi-Qar 2006;2(2):1–8.Search in Google Scholar">43</a>]. The DU concentration in soil and metal pieces near war zone in this study proved to have the highest concentration [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_044_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac44Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_044_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac44Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="44. Nada FT, Ali Sh MH, Ahmed AM. Assessment of depleted uranium contamination in selective Iraqi soils. J Al-Nahrain Uni – Sci 2008;11(1):74–81.10.22401/JNUS.11.1.10Search in Google Scholar">44</a>]. In one study [<a href="#j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_033_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac33Aa" class="link link-bibr" data-bs-target="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_033_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ac33Aa" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="33. Najeba Abdulah H, Nada Fadil T, Sabiha AB. Measurement of uranium concentration in soil of middle of Iraq using CR’V 39 track detector. Baghdad Sci J 2011;8(2):451–5.10.21123/bsj.8.2.451-455Search in Google Scholar">33</a>] it was found to be 16.38 ppm.</p></section></section><section id="j_reveh-2015-0024_s_006_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab1b5Aa"><h2 class="subheading">Conclusion</h2><p>The presence of a heavily contaminated environment with war related pollutants in most Iraqi cities needs great attention and huge effort to reduce the related health problems. Most of the studies done by Iraqi researchers and international collaborators confirmed the correlation between cancerous diseases and the munitions made of DU and years of wars leads to contaminate the Iraqi environment and causes a high risk to people in Iraq. Plans should include investigating the Iraqi environment from north to south especially the war zones where the DU ammunitions were used to identify the concentration of these pollutants and make plans to treat them. Treating the environmental pollutions near the war zones should be a maximum priority.</p><p>More resources should be offered to study the pollution effect on Iraqi personal health. The top priority is to increase awareness for the early detection for birth defects and congenital anomalies in the polluted areas. From a one health approach perspective, effective prevention and control of the pollution needs close collaboration between veterinarians, agriculturalist and public health professionals. A comprehensive screening for all effected animals should be done to eliminate the affected animals and food, and to avoid agriculture in the affected areas, which is particularly important, as there is no effective way to clean the soil. In addition, efforts should be made to increase the awareness of veterinarians and clinician as well as agriculture engineers along with the environmental health specialist for this environmental pollution to improve related disease prevention strategies.</p></section></div><section class="authorNotes"><hr></hr><div class="correspondingAuthor">Corresponding author: Ahmed Majeed Al-Shammari, Experimental Therapy Department, Iraqi Centre for Cancer and Medical Genetic Research, Al-Mustansiriyah University, Baghdad, Iraq, E-mail: <span class="email">Ahmed.alshammari@iccmgr.org</span></div><hr></hr></section><div class="contrib-group"></div><div class="back"><span class="ref-list"><h2 class="subheading">References</h2><p class="reference" id="j_reveh-2015-0024_ref_001_w2aab2b8c13b1b7b1ab2ab1Aa"><span class="reference-label d-inlineblock me-4">1. </span><span class="reference-mixed-citation">Brown VJ. Reconstructing the environment in Iraq. Environ Health Perspect 2004;112(8):A464.</span><span class="newline"></span><a href="https://doi.org/10.1289/ehp.112-a464" class="link link-external doi" rel="noopener noreferrer nofollow" target="_blank">10.1289/ehp.112-a464</a><span class="newline"></span><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=Brown%20VJ.%20Reconstructing%20the%20environment%20in%20Iraq.%20Environ%20Health%20Perspect%202004%3B112%288%29%3AA464." class="link link-external googleScholar" rel="noopener noreferrer nofollow" target="_blank">Search in Google Scholar</a><span class="newline"></span><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15175192/" class="link link-external pubmed" rel="noopener noreferrer nofollow" target="_blank">
